Yung Regression Correction

Regression Confounding Correction Method

Here I am testing the method derived by CNYung in his masters dissertation for correcting GWAS summary statistics.

He presents two models, 0 and 1, where they are unadjusted and adjusted for ancestry confounding, respectively. We can relate the two models.

\[ \beta_{0,j} = \beta_{1,j} + \phi_1\omega_{1,j} + ... + \phi_m\omega_{m,j} \]

Where:

\[ \omega_{k,j}: = \frac{\alpha_{k,j}}{\sqrt{\overline{\alpha_j}(1-\overline{\alpha_j})}} \] for k = 1,,m , where m is the number of anestry groups, and j is the SNP, and \(\alpha\) is the allele frequency. Therefore, \(\alpha_{k,j}\) is the reference allele frequency for ancestry k, and \(\overline{\alpha_j}\) is the mean allele frequency across all ancestries, m, or the observed AF. And also that means \(\omega_{k,j}\) represents the standardized allele frequency.

Testing this method

We want to test 4 scenarios:

AF std? Optimize
Summix Regression
std AF ? CNYung
raw AF OURS ?

He simulated:

  • ancestry group proportions
  • AF
  • ancestry-weighted AF means
  • raw and standardized SNP data
  • raw and standardized phenotypes

# ------------ NEW ------------------
rho = 0.65 # pairwise correlation between normal random variables used in copula
# rho is the average correlation between the group AFs 
# I tested AFR - EUR which was ~.65, so I'll try that
# C N Yung used .95 - which would be more like finescale

# simulate AFs for each group
alpha = t(matrix(
  pnorm(
    MASS::mvrnorm(
      n = nrow(chr19_sub),
      mu = rep(0, NAnc),
      Sigma = rho * (rep(1, NAnc) %*% t(rep(1, NAnc))) + (1 - rho) * diag(NAnc)
    )
  ),
  ncol = NAnc
))

# across-group ancestry-weighted means of those frequencies at each SNP
alpha_bar = colMeans(as.matrix(X_ancestryProps)) %*% alpha
#Check correlation between alphas (reference AFs)
plot(alpha[1,], alpha[2,])

DescTools::CCC(alpha[1,], alpha[2,])$rho.c$est
[1] 0.6301556
# simulate genotypes where each row is an individual and each column is the AC for each SNP
# uses alpha (allele frequencies)
# CURRENTLY USING ALPHA_BAR, WANT TO ALSO TEST USING SUMMIX AF_OBS I think?
genos <- matrix(0, nrow = NObs, ncol = nrow(chr19_sub)) 
genos_std <- genos
for(j in 1:ncol(genos)) {
  raw_geno <- rbinom(NObs, size = 2, prob = as.matrix(X_ancestryProps) %*% alpha[,j])
  if(length(unique(raw_geno) == 1)) { # ensure all individuals don't have same genotype count
    # otherwise will end up with zero variance
    if(unique(raw_geno)[1] == 1) {
      raw_geno[1] <- 0
    } else {
      raw_geno[1] <- 1
    }
  }
  genos[,j] <- raw_geno
  genos_std[,j] <- (genos[,j]-mean(genos[,j])) / sd(genos[,j])
}



# simulate phenotypes, raw and centered
gamma = 0.05 # proportion of variance of phenotype explained by ancestry

W <- rnorm(NObs, mean = 0, sd = 1)
tau <- sqrt((gamma/(1-gamma))/(sum(as.matrix(X_ancestryProps)^2)/NObs))
mu <- rnorm(NAnc, mean = 0, sd = tau)

raw_phenotype <- as.matrix(X_ancestryProps) %*% mu + W

# center the phenotypes
centered_phenotype <- scale(raw_phenotype, scale = F)

# check phenotype looks OK
hist(centered_phenotype)

results <- data.frame(coef_no_anc = rep(0, NSNPs), # beta_0j
                      coef_with_anc = rep(0, NSNPs), #beta_1j
                      z_no_anc = rep(0, NSNPs),
                      z_with_anc = rep(0, NSNPs),
                      p_no_anc = rep(0, NSNPs),
                      p_with_anc = rep(0, NSNPs))


for(j in 1:nrow(chr19_sub)) {
  alldata <- data.frame(Y = centered_phenotype,
                      X_afr = X_ancestryProps$prop_afr,
                      X_eur = X_ancestryProps$prop_eur,
                      Z = genos_std[,j])
  # first do model 0 without ancestry
  mod_no_anc <- lm(Y ~ 0 + ., data = alldata[ ,c(1, NAnc+2)])
  results[j,]$coef_no_anc <- summary(mod_no_anc)$coef[1] 
  results[j,]$z_no_anc <- summary(mod_no_anc)$coef[3]
  results[j,]$p_no_anc <- summary(mod_no_anc)$coef[4]
  
  # now do model 1 with ancestry
  mod_with_anc <- lm(Y ~ 0 + ., data = alldata)
  results[j,]$coef_with_anc <- summary(mod_with_anc)$coef[3, 1] 
  results[j,]$z_with_anc <- summary(mod_with_anc)$coef[3,3]
  results[j,]$p_with_anc <- summary(mod_with_anc)$coef[3,4]
  
  if(j %% 1000 == 0) {
    print(paste0("SNP ", j, " done"))
  }
}

                           omega1 = omega1,

# use regression of beta0 and z0 on omega_k's to back out of the adjusted coefficients and z-score respectively
coef_summary_mod <- lm(summary_data[ , c(1, 3:(NAnc+2))])
z_summary_mod <- lm(summary_data[ ,c(2:(NAnc+2))])
phi_hat <- coef_summary_mod$coef[2:(NAnc+1)]
theta_hat <- z_summary_mod$coef[2:(NAnc+1)]

omega1phi1 <- summary_data$omega1 * phi_hat[1]
omega2phi2 <- summary_data$omega2 * phi_hat[2]
beta1 <- results$coef_no_anc - omega1phi1 - omega2phi2

adjusted_coef <- results$coef_no_anc - as.matrix(summary_data[ , 3:4]) %*% phi_hat
adjusted_z <- results$z_no_anc - as.matrix(summary_data[ ,3:4]) %*% theta_hat

results <- results %>%
  mutate(adjusted_coef = adjusted_coef,
         adjusted_z = adjusted_z)

ggplot(results, aes(x = coef_with_anc, y = adjusted_coef)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_text(aes(x = -0.05, y = 0.045), label = CCC(results$coef_with_anc, results$adjusted_coef)$rho.c$est)

OK the answer is no, it doesnt work with that simulation method for reference AFs

What happens if you include a reference ancestry thats not actually present in the ancestry proportions?

alpha = t(matrix(
  pnorm(
    MASS::mvrnorm(
      n = nrow(chr19_sub),
      mu = rep(0, NAnc),

alpha_bar = colMeans(as.matrix(X_ancestryProps)) %*% alpha

# simulate genotypes where each row is an individual and each column is the AC for each SNP
# uses alpha (allele frequencies)
genos <- matrix(0, nrow = NObs, ncol = nrow(chr19_sub)) 
genos_std <- genos
for(j in 1:ncol(genos)) {
  raw_geno <- rbinom(NObs, size = 2, prob = as.matrix(X_ancestryProps) %*% alpha[,j])
  if(length(unique(raw_geno) == 1)) { # ensure all individuals don't have same genotype count
    # otherwise will end up with zero variance
    if(unique(raw_geno)[1] == 1) {
      raw_geno[1] <- 0
    } else {
      raw_geno[1] <- 1
    }
  }
  genos[,j] <- raw_geno
  genos_std[,j] <- (genos[,j]-mean(genos[,j])) / sd(genos[,j])
}



# simulate phenotypes, raw and centered
gamma = 0.05 # proportion of variance of phenotype explained by ancestry

W <- rnorm(NObs, mean = 0, sd = 1)
tau <- sqrt((gamma/(1-gamma))/(sum(as.matrix(X_ancestryProps)^2)/NObs))
mu <- rnorm(NAnc, mean = 0, sd = tau)

raw_phenotype <- as.matrix(X_ancestryProps) %*% mu + W

# center the phenotypes
centered_phenotype <- scale(raw_phenotype, scale = F)

# ------------------------------------------------------------------

results <- data.frame(coef_no_anc = rep(0, NSNPs), # beta_0j
                      coef_with_anc = rep(0, NSNPs), #beta_1j

                      z_with_anc = rep(0, NSNPs),
                      p_no_anc = rep(0, NSNPs),
                      p_with_anc = rep(0, NSNPs))


for(j in 1:nrow(chr19_sub)) {
  alldata <- data.frame(Y = centered_phenotype,
                      X_afr = X_ancestryProps$prop_afr,
                      X_eur = X_ancestryProps$prop_eur,
                      X_iam = X_ancestryProps$prop_iam,
                      Z = genos_std[,j])
  # first do model 0 without ancestry
  mod_no_anc <- lm(Y ~ 0 + ., data = alldata[ ,c(1, NAnc+2)])
  results[j,]$coef_no_anc <- summary(mod_no_anc)$coef[1] 
  results[j,]$z_no_anc <- summary(mod_no_anc)$coef[3]
  results[j,]$p_no_anc <- summary(mod_no_anc)$coef[4]
  
  # now do model 1 with ancestry
  mod_with_anc <- lm(Y ~ 0 + ., data = alldata)
  results[j,]$coef_with_anc <- summary(mod_with_anc)$coef[(NAnc+1), 1] 
  results[j,]$z_with_anc <- summary(mod_with_anc)$coef[(NAnc+1),3]
  results[j,]$p_with_anc <- summary(mod_with_anc)$coef[(NAnc+1),4]
  
  if(j %% 1000 == 0) {
    print(paste0("SNP ", j, " done"))

}

                      X_iam = X_ancestryProps$prop_iam,
                      Z = genos_std[,j])
  # first do model 0 without ancestry
  mod_no_anc <- lm(Y ~ 0 + ., data = alldata[ ,c(1, NAnc+2)])
  results[j,]$coef_no_anc <- summary(mod_no_anc)$coef[1] 
  results[j,]$z_no_anc <- summary(mod_no_anc)$coef[3]
  results[j,]$p_no_anc <- summary(mod_no_anc)$coef[4]
  
  # now do model 1 with ancestry
  mod_with_anc <- lm(Y ~ 0 + ., data = alldata)
  results[j,]$coef_with_anc <- summary(mod_with_anc)$coef[(NAnc+1), 1] 
  results[j,]$z_with_anc <- summary(mod_with_anc)$coef[(NAnc+1),3]
  results[j,]$p_with_anc <- summary(mod_with_anc)$coef[(NAnc+1),4]
  
  if(j %% 1000 == 0) {
    print(paste0("SNP ", j, " done"))
  }
}
